AB  - South Africa imposed lockdown level five to curb the spread of the COVID-19 virus. Businesses and shops had to close, adding to the hardships because of the lockout. Furthermore, employees chose to stay at home because of the lack of notice, resulting in job losses. Many people nowadays stay at home to do activities like surfing social media and watching videos online. Users can contact businesses via the Internet, but not all of them can be trusted. When people go shopping, they frequently overestimate their needs and end up spending more money than they should. The idea that purchasers are influenced by variables outside of the store when making purchases is one of the more dated beliefs about consumer behaviour that is still applicable today. The conceptualisation of this literary work is informed by both the Uses and Gratification Theory and the Hawkins Stern‘s Theory of Impulsive Purchases. Using a quantitative method and convenient sampling, this study evaluated how people's purchasing patterns were altered because of the lockdown. A total of 384 people volunteered to participate in the study. The results collected were computed with the use of the Statistical Package for the Social Sciences (SPSS) software, and Microsoft Excel was used for data analysis. The study concluded that, despite the shutdown, South Africans are not easily swayed by social media influence. The study recommended that, to mitigate the negative effects of social media‘s influence on people‘s spending of money during the lockdown, the community needs to collaborate with the Communications and Marketing Division of the University of Zululand and organise a seminar by the community leaders involving the municipality of the selected rural area. However, financial entities should be consulted to educate consumers on financial literacy. Consumers should be encouraged to avoid overdependence on social media. © 2024 Adonis and Abbey Publishers Ltd. All rights reserved.
